1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:11,700
(1 John 4:9): ‘In this was manifested the love of God toward us that he sent his only-begotten Son into the world that we might live with the Son,’ that is, ‘in and through the Son.

2
00:00:11,650 --> 00:00:15,237
Those that live not through the Son, verily they err.

3
00:00:15,237 --> 00:00:23,125
If a mighty king had a beautiful daughter and gave her to a poor man’s son, every member of his family would rise in rank and become ennobled.

4
00:00:23,125 --> 00:00:38,075
Thus one learned doctor says: ‘By God becoming man the whole human race has been ennobled and exalted; wherefore it behoves us to rejoice greatly that Christ our brother has with peculiar power ascended up above the choir of angels and sitteth on the right hand of the Father.

5
00:00:38,075 --> 00:00:41,850
This is well said, though I set but little store by it.

6
00:00:41,850 --> 00:00:47,062
What profit to me that my brother is rich if I am poor, or wise and I a fool?

7
00:00:47,062 --> 00:00:53,175
I say something more and more significant: God not only became man, he assumed human nature.

8
00:00:53,175 --> 00:00:57,037
Doctors agree that all men are of equal rank by nature.

9
00:00:57,037 --> 00:01:06,425
But I make bold to say that every good thing possessed by the saints and by Mary, God’s mother, and Christ in his human nature, is also mine in this same nature.

10
00:01:06,425 --> 00:01:16,087
Haply thou wilt ask me: ‘If already I possess in this nature all that Christ does in his humanity, how come we to set Christ so high and honour him as our Lord and God?

11
00:01:16,087 --> 00:01:20,475
Because he was a messenger from God to us, bringing us our happiness.

12
00:01:20,475 --> 00:01:23,125
The happiness he brought us was our own.

13
00:01:23,125 --> 00:01:28,550
When the Father begets his Son in the innermost ground, what moves there has this nature.

14
00:01:28,550 --> 00:01:31,562
This same nature is one and indivisible.

15
00:01:31,562 --> 00:01:35,400
Anything distinct in it or connected with it is not this one.

16
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:38,000
Another thing I say, still harder.

17
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:49,050
To subsist immediately in this pure nature a man must be so wholly dead to person that he wills as well to one across the seas whom his eyes have never seen as to his own present and familiar friend.

18
00:01:49,050 --> 00:01:58,887
While thou still wishest better to thine own person than to that man whom thou hast never seen thou art beside the mark, nor hast thou even for an instant seen into this simple ground.

19
00:01:58,887 --> 00:02:04,937
Haply in some far-fetched symbol thou hast beheld the truth as in an image, but it was not the best.

20
00:02:04,937 --> 00:02:11,425
Secondly, thou must be pure in heart; and only that heart is pure which has exterminated creaturehood.

21
00:02:11,425 --> 00:02:14,375
And thirdly, thou must be free from not.

22
00:02:14,375 --> 00:02:17,162
It is a question, what burns in hell?

23
00:02:17,162 --> 00:02:20,437
Doctors reply with one accord: ‘self-will.

24
00:02:20,437 --> 00:02:23,325
But I maintain: not burns in hell.

25
00:02:23,325 --> 00:02:24,350
A simile!

26
00:02:24,350 --> 00:02:31,512
Suppose I take a burning coal and put it on my hand; then if I say the coal is burning me, I do it great injustice.

27
00:02:31,512 --> 00:02:38,375
To define precisely what it is that burns me: not does; because the coal has in it something my hand has not.

28
00:02:38,375 --> 00:02:41,550
Observe, it is this very not that burns me.

29
00:02:41,550 --> 00:02:47,325
Did my hand contain what the coal is and can afford, it would possess the fire-nature altogether.

30
00:02:47,325 --> 00:02:53,462
In which case all the fire that ever burned might be taken and heaped upon my hand without its burning me.

31
00:02:53,462 --> 00:03:07,400
Likewise, I aver that because God and those who are in sight of God, have in them something pertaining to real happiness which those who are apart from God have not, therefore this not alone torments the souls in hell more than the personal will or any fire soever.

32
00:03:07,400 --> 00:03:12,675
In sooth I hold: as far as not inheres in thee, so far thou art imperfect.

33
00:03:12,675 --> 00:03:16,475
To be perfect, then, thou must be free from not.

34
00:03:16,588 --> 00:03:26,625
Further, my text says: ‘God sent his only-begotten Son into the world,’ by which ye are to understand not the external world: it must be taken of the inner world.

35
00:03:26,575 --> 00:03:35,925
As surely as the Father by his simple nature begets the Son innately, so surely he begets him in the innermost recesses of the mind, which is the inner world.

36
00:03:35,925 --> 00:03:39,913
Here God’s ground is my ground and my ground God’s ground.

37
00:03:39,913 --> 00:03:43,063
Here I live in my own as God lives in his own.

38
00:03:43,063 --> 00:03:50,788
To one who even for an instant has seen into this ground, a thousand ducats of red beaten gold are worth no more than a false farthing.

39
00:03:50,788 --> 00:03:54,913
Out of this innermost ground thy works should be wrought without why.

40
00:03:54,913 --> 00:04:05,750
Indeed, I hold that as long as thou doest thy works because of the kingdom of heaven, or God, or thine own eternal happiness, from without (that is to say), all is not well with thee.

41
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:08,775
It may be tolerable but it is not the best.

42
00:04:08,775 --> 00:04:22,613
He who fondly imagines to get more of God in thoughts, prayers, pious offices and so forth, than by the fireside or in the stall: in sooth he does but take God, as it were, and swaddle his head in a cloak and hide him under the table.

43
00:04:22,613 --> 00:04:28,713
For he who seeks God under settled forms lays hold of the form while missing the God concealed in it.

44
00:04:28,713 --> 00:04:37,063
But he who seeks God in no special guise lays hold of him as he is in himself, and such an one ‘lives with the Son’ and is the life itself.

45
00:04:37,063 --> 00:04:41,338
We might question life for a thousand years: ‘Why dost thou live?

46
00:04:41,338 --> 00:04:45,688
It would only say, if it replied at all, ‘I live because I live.

47
00:04:45,688 --> 00:04:49,713
For life lives in a ground of its own, wells up out of its own.

48
00:04:49,713 --> 00:04:52,813
It lives without a cause for it lives itself.

49
00:04:52,813 --> 00:05:01,813
And if anyone asked a proper man, one who works his own ground, ‘Why dost thou work?’ he too would say, if he told the truth: ‘I work because I work.

50
00:05:01,813 --> 00:05:04,850
Where creature stops, there God begins.

51
00:05:04,850 --> 00:05:11,425
All God wants of thee is for thee to go out of thyself in respect of thy creatureliness and let God be God in thee.

52
00:05:11,425 --> 00:05:17,125
The smallest of creaturely images that ever takes shape in thee is as big as God.—‘How so?

53
00:05:17,125 --> 00:05:19,288
It shuts out the whole of God.

54
00:05:19,288 --> 00:05:23,563
As soon as this image appears God disappears with all his Godhead.

55
00:05:23,563 --> 00:05:26,325
As this image fades out God comes in.

56
00:05:26,325 --> 00:05:30,288
No temporal image is so godly but thrice harms the soul.

57
00:05:30,288 --> 00:05:37,938
First, it vexes spirituality; next, it tarnishes her purity; and thirdly, it disturbs detachment.

58
00:05:37,938 --> 00:05:40,213
What does God do to my mind?

59
00:05:40,213 --> 00:05:44,800
Transcend thyself and repress creatures: God does that to thy mind.

60
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:52,550
God longs as urgently for thee to go out of thyself in respect of thy creaturely nature as though his whole felicity depended on it.

61
00:05:52,550 --> 00:05:56,600
Why, man, what is the harm of letting God be God in thee?

62
00:05:56,600 --> 00:06:01,988
Go clean out of thy self for God’s sake, and God will go clean out of his for thy sake.

63
00:06:01,988 --> 00:06:05,525
Both being gone out, what remains is simply the one.

64
00:06:05,525 --> 00:06:10,100
In this one the Father gives birth to his Son, in his innermost source.

65
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:15,750
Thence blossoms forth the Holy Ghost and thence originates in God the will belonging to the soul.

66
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:21,238
The while this will remains unmoved by creatures and by creaturehood, the will is free.

67
00:06:21,238 --> 00:06:25,425
Christ says: ‘None goes to heaven but he who came from heaven.

68
00:06:25,425 --> 00:06:29,575
Things are all made from nothing; hence their true source is nothing.

69
00:06:29,575 --> 00:06:35,125
This noble will, as far as it inclines to creatures, with them elapses into nothing.

70
00:06:35,125 --> 00:06:40,000
The question is, Does the will lapse so far that it is never able to return?

71
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:45,438
Doctors reply with one accord that it does not return so far as it has lapsed with time.

72
00:06:45,438 --> 00:06:57,650
But I maintain that if this will turns back, even for an instant, from its own self and things created and rallies to its source, there in its own free origin the will is free and in this instant time lost is all recovered.

73
00:06:57,650 --> 00:07:00,463
People often say to me: ‘Pray for me.

74
00:07:00,463 --> 00:07:03,825
And I think to myself: Why ever do ye go out?

75
00:07:03,825 --> 00:07:06,788
Why not stop at home and mine your own treasure?

76
00:07:06,788 --> 00:07:09,750
For indeed the whole truth is native in you.

77
00:07:09,750 --> 00:07:17,000
May we be apt to stay thus in ourselves and to possess the entire truth immediately, impartibly, in real happiness.

78
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:18,600
So help us God!

79
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:19,525
Amen.
